metadata.name: Bento Boxes #47
metadata.description:
Everybody needs a bento box in the cryptowinter.
The project calls for an adopted nostalgia of little kids that has been handed bento box by their parents before school‚Äî a little moment of protected comfort before heading out for an adventure.

‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢

The first collaboration project of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. A work based on MEK.txt‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Bento Boxes‚Äù and IceRain‚Äôs excellent codes, Bento Boxes aims to be a fun visual and code exploration project on the generative art corridor. Pure code, no libraries.

Bento Boxes deconstructed the visual system on MEK.txt's artwork, titled almost similarly, ‚ÄúThe Bento Boxes‚Äù. Rebuilt it from scratch with codes, adding variants of colours and shapes‚Äî without losing the strong characteristics of the base artwork.

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #55
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.

metadata.name: dg5721() #64
metadata.description:
A tiny neural network with 5721 neurons, that tries to imitate human handwriting by generating new hallucinated digits in real-time.

It can generate these digits at any resolution and will invent its own ways to fill the gaps.

- Press <SPACE> or click to toggle the infinite latent space exploration.
- Press <S> to save the current frame as PNG at the current screen resolution x2.

It can be installed to work offline (Install button in the URL bar in Chrome or "Add to Home screen" on iOS)

As of 2021, this artwork requires a fast computer or mobile phone.

metadata.name: Skravert #264
metadata.description:
‚ÄòSkravert‚Äô - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‚ÄòThe act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area‚Äô.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Schwere See #17
metadata.description:
Schwere See (...which is german for "Heavy Seas") this work creates completely generative ocean worlds between the real and the surreal. what is real? when do we feel reality? i guess as with many other things, we feel reality best when we're deprived of it. That might be the reason why it never ceases to fascinate us to both exaggerate and abstract nature and reality - maybe even at the same time. that's where this work tries to go... giving my best to create realistic looking waves out of hmm... thin electron-gas..., and then disrupt those from realism by unnaturally exaggerating waveforms and abstracting the display to a few colors and lines - ...well, not so few of the latter, actually ;-) beware: this needs a good GPU (at least here in 2023) to properly run in realtime. stills can still be rendered on a low end machine with on-board graphics, but for realtime playing you'd need some proper dedicated graphics card. and of course it wont run fast (or maybe not all) on your mobile phone (except maybe on a very high end device). the different mints vary in wave shape, color, camera view, animation speed, aspect ratio, frame style, hatching density, field of view, and more. some color schemes are based on pre-chosen palettes (slightly varied though), but others are wildly random-generated. there's always some risk in randomness, but lets give the error some chance to surprise us - this is one of the many benefits of generative art. as generative art can do so much more than just generate/show an image i feel almost obliged to add the possibility to animate/inteact. however, this extra control shall not be chosen without some considerations. you don't want a strobingly wild animation above your fireplace or in a doctors waiting room. nor is it motion-wise very inspiring to have subtle image stills hanging in a dancefloor. so, by default when in animation mode (-key) the scene is very slowly and steadily changing - some pieces faster, some slower. however, by pressing you can toggle to a sped up animation of waves, clouds, and scene rotation. btw, going faster in nav-mode also speeds up the wave animation. (...so be careful when you accelerate! the ocean is not a ponyfarm.) mouse/keyboard functions: ..........rotate view .........zoom in/out ...............start animation (or append '&AnimEnable=1' to the url) +<1><2><3><4>...make png screenshot in 1/2/3/4-fold resolution

...................same as +<3> ...................toggle nav-mode - navigate/fly through scene /.........accelerate in nav-mode /.......decelerate in nav-mode /.......rotate left in nav-mode /......rotate right in nav-mode ...................fast animation mode (speeds up animation) some technical info: technically this is a raymarched scene. the distance field of the waves is constructed my many localized rotations on many different scales. for the hatching no actual lines are being drawn. it is archieved by applying periodic functions in world-position-space as halftone patterns to the actual image color. the frequency of these halftone-functions thereby depending on screen-position-derivatives.

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #61
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
‚ÄúIn Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art‚Äù 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke‚Äôs MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it‚Äôs a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

‚ÄúOur goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke‚Äôs 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the R√ºtgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.‚Äù 

Each frame, a single ‚Äúpixel‚Äù is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely ‚Äî it‚Äôs an ‚Äúinfinite animation.‚Äù
